Unexpectedly fantastic sushi!

I have enjoyed so much, that I came back the next evening.

This is our first visit since their upgrade. Great new menus, including the menu from their sister restaurant chain, Negishi and a drink menu with clever non-alcoholic options. We are certain to make this a regular haunt.

The staff are very nice, fast service, well curated menus: All would be perfect except for one thing. This may not bother some people, but it did concern me. If you need to use silverware, you have to take it out of a utensil bucket on the table. The spoons and forks are facing business end up. This means that when somebody pulls one out, the utensils next to them are being touched as well. Unless you just use chopsticks or order a large soup that comes with a spoon, you may be putting your mouth where a stranger put their hand :-(

Only some people would be bothered by this, but I really think they need to change how silverware is provisioned.

Other than that, the reinvented Nooch @ Barfi is a hard place to beat for Asian food in Basel.

You definitely need to know what to order. So, if you want to eat here for the first time and don't know what to order: Definitely go for their Beijing Night (i like mine without pineapples), if you like chicken and rice. Try their Sunshine Surfers, if you like noodles. Their range of soupy noodles are okayish. Their Dim Zuma (version of Shu mai) is also very nice. I however do not like their Thai range of dishes.

I ordered online take away and when my husband got there they told us no order has been placed. Even though I received a confirmation. I hoped at least the food was worth the waiting and the hastle, but the Vietnamese food was not authentic, you could smell that it was just beef-cube, and the noodles were still hard. My family and I were visiting from the US and came here and were ripped off by the waiter. We asked for water and he told us that there was “draught water”, which we assumed to be tap water, he gave us no other options. He did not once mention that there was a giant sink and “free water” for anyone to help themselves to, so we ordered the water and carried on with our night. When it came time to pay, the water cost 17 CF for three people. When we asked the waiter about this, he told us this was the price for draught water. It seems to us quite obvious that he intentionally mislead us and took advantage of our naivety in a foreign country in order to charge us more.
